headline: The Week in Numbers: Brand sales to Travis Kelce's marketing boost
summary:
STORY: From a major brand sale to Travis Kelce's marketing boost, this is the Week in Numbers.

:: The Week in Numbers

:: $4.6 billion

$4.6 billion is the price Gucci owner Kering has agreed on to sell its beauty business to L'Oreal.

It's a major shift in strategy by new CEO Luca de Meo in a bid to tackle the luxury group's high debt....

And to refocus on its core fashion business.

Under the deal, beauty giant L'Oreal will acquire Kering's fragrance line Creed.

:: 10%

:: Intel Corporation 

Almost 10% is the amount Intel stocks hiked early Friday after the company beat estimates for its Q3 earnings. 

Net income came in at $4.1 billion - compared to a $16.6 billion loss the same time last year.

The silicon giant's shares have hiked 90% this year. 

And this marks the first earnings announcement after multibillion-dollar investments from Nvidia and Softbank - as well as an unprecedented U.S. government stake.

:: 5%

Around 5% was how much oil prices surged early Thursday. 

Markets reacted after the U.S. put sanctions on leading Russian suppliers Rosneft and Lukoil over the Ukraine war.

One analyst said this means refineries in China and India, both major buyers of Russia's oil, will need to find other suppliers or risk exclusion from the Western banking system. 

The U.S. said it was prepared to take further action as it called on Moscow to agree to a ceasefire in Ukraine.

:: 33% 

:: Volvo 

Over a third was how much Volvo Cars shares soared on Thursday.

Investors bought up after the automaker announced it beat Q3 profit forecasts.

Sweeping cost cuts have delivered faster than expected results.

That's despite Volvo being one of the European carmakers most exposed to U.S. tariffs.

:: 20%

20% is the figure Six Flags shares have climbed by this week as the company faces shareholder pressure. 

Activist investor Jana Partners has teamed up with football star Travis Kelce to push the company to improve its marketing and customer experiences after disclosing a 9% stake.

Kelce is star tight end for the NFL‚Äôs Kansas City Chiefs and podcast host who recently got engaged to singer Taylor Swift.

headline: Intel beats Q3 profit estimates as cost cuts, investments pay off
summary:
STORY: :: Intel Corporation

Intel's stock jumped as the company beat estimates for its third quarter earnings on Thursday.

The company said it earned an adjusted 23 cents a share on sales of $13.7 billion - outperforming expectations of a profit of 1 cent per share.

Net income came in at $4.1 billion - compared to a $16.6 billion loss the same time last year.

It marks the silicon giant's first earnings announcement after multibillion-dollar investments from Nvidia and Softbank as well as an unprecedented stake from the U.S. government.

The turnaround comes after CEO Lip-Bu Tan's drastic cost-cutting measures - beside paring back expensive manufacturing processes, Intel will end this year with a workforce that is over one-fifth smaller than a year ago.

Intel's share price dropped about 60% last year, after concerns it would struggle to rival AMD in making PCs and CPUs, and Intel's fruitless attempts at breaking into the AI chip market.

Now in 2025, Intel stock has risen nearly 90% so far, outperforming Nvidia.

It forecasts a fourth quarter revenue between $12.8 to $13.8 billion.

Intel's finance chief Dave Zinsner said on a conference call, demand for Intel's chips was strong enough during the third quarter that the company is tight on supply.

However for its high-efficiency 18A chips, he said yields for those - a measure of how many chips come out usable - would not be at an industry-accepted level until 2027. 

Reuters reported in August that Intel is struggling with yields on its 18A manufacturing technology.

headline: Intel shares jump as investments, cost cuts catapult turnaround efforts
summary: (Reuters) -Intel shares surged as much as 7.8% in early trading on Friday, hitting an 18-month high, as investors rallied behind CEO Lip-Bu Tan's aggressive cost-cutting measures that helped the chipmaker surpass quarterly profit estimates and regain stability amid a flurry of high-stakes bets on future growth.  The results mark a turning point for Intel, which has struggled to maintain relevance in the face of fierce competition and manufacturing setbacks.  After a bruising 2024 that saw its first annual loss in nearly four decades, the company is now leaning on strategic investments and operational discipline to rebuild investor confidence.

headline: Wall Street hits records following an encouraging update on inflation
summary: The Dow Jones Industrial Average rallied 472 points, or 1%, and the Nasdaq composite climbed 1.1%.  The Fed just cut its main interest rate last month for the first time this year, but it‚Äôs been hesitant to promise more relief because lower rates can make inflation worse, beyond goosing the economy and prices for investments.  Following the inflation report, traders continue to bet on a near certainty that the Fed will cut rates at its next two meetings, including one next week.
